  # County could approve first overnight accommodation in a year and a half
  
  Luxury glamping development’s fate soon to be decided.
  
  [By Editor Moabtimes](https://www.moabtimes.com/author/editormoabtimes-com/)
  
  on
  January 09, 2024
  
  [By Gwen Dilworth](https://www.moabtimes.com/author/By+Gwen+Dilworth)
  
  [Facebook](https://www.moabtimes.com/#facebook "Facebook") [Twitter](https://www.moabtimes.com/#twitter "Twitter") [Email](https://www.moabtimes.com/#email "Email") [Messenger](https://www.moabtimes.com/#facebook_messenger "Messenger") [Copy Link](https://www.moabtimes.com/#copy_link "Copy Link") [Message](https://www.moabtimes.com/#sms "Message") [Share](https://www.addtoany.com/share#url=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.moabtimes.com%2Farticles%2Fcounty-could-approve-first-overnight-accommodation-in-a-year-and-a-half%2F&title=County%20could%20approve%20first%20overnight%20accommodation%20in%20a%20year%20and%20a%20half)
  
  The Entrada Moab luxury glamping development — now two years in the making — will have to wait a little longer.
  
  ![](https://www.moabtimes.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/01/02-entrada-moab-mockup.png)Entrada Moab’s luxury accommodations are expected to rake in an average daily rate of $2,000 per unit per night. _File photo_
  
  However, it will most likely not wait nine months or until the Planning and Zoning Department revisits the land-use code to define “glamping” — glamorous camping — as proposed by the Planning Commission in October.
  
  At their Jan. 2 meeting, most commissioners indicated they are interested in approving an overnight accommodations zoning overlay for the development, citing its opportunity for diversifying the tourism sector with its luxury accommodations and yielding high Transient Room Tax (TRT) revenue despite its minimal impact.
  
  Commissioner Trish Hedin voiced a lone strong dissent. “We get a lot of feedback from the lodging community that their occupancy rates are not high enough and now we have another lodging entity coming forward, so to me, it just exacerbates the issues,” Hedin said. She also said she was concerned by the plan’s lack of a reliable water source, flooding and disruptions to bighorn sheep habitat.
  
  The commission unanimously agreed to table their vote on approval of the overlay until their next meeting.
  
  County Attorney Stephen Stocks said he did not think it would be fair to ask the developer to wait another nine months or be held to different regulations than when the developer, Matt Kareus of Fort Collins, Colorado, originally applied. “I think we should give a response to an applicant,” he said. “When an applicant applies, we give them the laws that are in place at the time, we can’t change … the rules on them.”
  
  He encouraged commissioners to delay the vote for two weeks to give him time to draft guidance that would prevent the commission from reaching an outcome that could “subject \[the county\] to more scrutiny or litigation.” He cited concerns about the commission’s decision involving a “quid pro quo,” or approval of the overlay in return for certain conditions.
  
  “We don’t want there to be that perception that we’re going outside of what the land use code is for us to approve \[an application\],” he said.
  
  The proposed 16-unit “eco-retreat” will include a spa, swimming pools, trails and an adventure center on a plot of land near the intersection of Highway 191 and Highway 313. The proposal anticipates an average daily rate of $2,000 per room each night.
  
  The site is owned by Moab-based Intrepid Potash.
  
  The project was first denied for a campground-specific overnight accommodations overlay in February 2022. However, the commission expressed interest in approving the proposal if it was adjusted to include employee housing and a permanent conservation easement.
  
  The modified proposal includes five on-site housing units for employees and 20 off-site, deed-restricted employee housing units that will be constructed in Grand County. It also includes a deed-restricted conservation easement on 136 acres of the property.
  
  ![](https://www.moabtimes.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/01/2-entrada-moab-meeting-primary-pic-1024x683.jpeg)Associate Planner Jenna Gorney presents the Entrada Moab proposal at the first Grand County Commission meeting of 2024.
  
  _Photo by Gwen Dilworth_
  
  “It seems to go hand in hand with what the county’s been wanting for years,” said Commissioner Mike McCurdy.
  
  In 2019, facing an onslaught of new hotels and overnight rentals, the county imposed a six-month moratorium on all new overnight accommodation approvals. When it expired, the commission changed the process for approval of overnight accommodations, requiring each to be greenlit by the commission.
  
  However, commissioners indicated at the time that the new rules were not an outright ban, but rather a process that privileged exceptional applications.
  
  “We gave our word that this was not going to bring a complete stop to overnight rentals,” said Commissioner Mary McGann.
  
  Since 2019, the county has approved only two overnight accommodations projects, both close to the Colorado border and far from Moab. The Sky Retreat, a 16-cabin development, was approved in 2021, and the 12-unit Tin Roof Cabin Resort was approved in June 2022.
  
  McCurdy applauded the developer for the changes he made to the project in response to the commission’s suggestions in 2022. “Thank you for the employee housing and the offsite employee housing and the promise of higher wages and a 150-acre conservation easement,” he said.
  
  Commission Vice Chair Kevin Walker said that while he thinks glamping is very silly — “I mean, who in the world would want to pay thousands of dollars to sleep in a tent,” he noted — the project does offer Grand County the opportunity to be a part of a popular new form of recreation.
  
  Commissioner Bill Winfield agreed. “They’re not high impact users,” he said.
  
  Commissioners McCurdy, McGann, Walker, Winfield and McGann indicated that they would be interested in approving the project at the Jan. 16 meeting.
  
  “I’ve liked this project from the beginning,” said McGann. “I would vote yes today without hesitation.”
  
  
