  # Moving snow…
  
  [By ohtadmin](https://www.moabtimes.com/author/ohtadmin/)
  
  on
  February 07, 2008
  
  [Facebook](https://www.moabtimes.com/#facebook "Facebook") [Twitter](https://www.moabtimes.com/#twitter "Twitter") [Email](https://www.moabtimes.com/#email "Email") [Messenger](https://www.moabtimes.com/#facebook_messenger "Messenger") [Copy Link](https://www.moabtimes.com/#copy_link "Copy Link") [Message](https://www.moabtimes.com/#sms "Message") [Share](https://www.addtoany.com/share#url=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.moabtimes.com%2Farticles%2Fmoving-snow%2F&title=Moving%20snow%E2%80%A6)
  
  The older the man, the smaller the shovel. This would explain why it took me so long to get all that snow removed from my walks and parking slab. I once owned the Rolls Royce (or should I say, Honda) of snow blowers. It was so pretty, all red and shiny. It would cast a plume of snow 40 feet high and 70 feet away. I bought it 12 years ago. I bought it in a fit of passion. I nursed the passion during all 13 hours it took me to shovel a road through my long driveway filled with 5 feet of drifted snow.
  
  With the new snow blower it took less than three hours to clear the other half of the drive, the walks and everything else. Wouldn’t you know? We didn’t get another such snow in the next several years. In fact, we still haven’t. Finally, one of my sons-in-law, who lives up north, gave me a decent price for the idle snow blower. He has used it several times.
  
  I like to think of myself as a good neighbor or, at least, not a bad neighbor. There was a large, young man living with the neighbors. When I finished digging myself out so that I could drive to purchase the new snow blower, and had used it to clear the rest of the place, the young man asked if he could borrow it.
  
  I’m sorry, but it irritated the heck out of me that he would ask. He had a distance of about 25 feet to clear from the back porch to the shed. The snow was only a couple of feet deep because it had not drifted there. He wasn’t doing anything else.
  
  I told him that he could not borrow the new snow blower. He made a subtle little shift and said that he hadn’t wanted to borrow it but would I bring it over and clear the path. I told him that I would not because I knew that there were dog dishes, bones and other clutter that would sheer off the pins in the auger. He said that there was nothing in the way. It was not true.
  
  In jest, I called my son-in-law up north to ask if he knew of anyone who would lend me a really nice snow blower.
  
  In the old days, when I was younger and my shovels were bigger, I shoveled a lot of snow. I took my shovel atop houses and removed the snow. I cleared many driveways. To tell the truth, I enjoyed it.
  
  There was one deep, and tightly packed pile of snow that had accumulated from slipping off the metal roof of a back porch. It was nearly as high as my head and I wanted to move it away from the house. Since the snow was so tightly packed I fired up my chainsaw and cut shovel-width grooves down through the snow and then chopped and shoveled the blocks of snow.
  
  Things have changed. There is something about a short-handled shovel that does not agree with an aging back. This last snow was heavy and wet. I went to work with the usual snow shovel but soon found the snow too heavy for the large blade. I went to the shed and got the square point shovel.
  
  I sprayed the metal square point with Pam, the stuff you spray into a frying pan to keep food from sticking. The Pam worked well as the snow did not stick to the shovel for the first few hours.
  
  Moving all that snow with a small shovel was like painting a large room with a small brush. It took many strokes. But, it did wonders for my case of cabin fever. Other than the occasional bicycle ride it was the first decent work I have done all winter, and it felt good.
  
  Best of all, I awoke the next morning without a single pain in my aging body. Maybe it’s an old-guy thing but waking up pain-free is something of a miracle and cause for celebration.
  
  The thing is, though, if I have to shovel much more snow it may be time to buy a blade for the four-wheeler.
  
  
